@harryallen Correct! The VIPER mission proposed the name to the International Astronomical Union as the IAU theme for naming mountains (mons) on the Moon focuses on ‚Äúscientists who have made outstanding or fundamental contributions to their fields.‚Äù https://t.co/Fng8iiGOWp

Have humans ever visited Mars?

Not yet, but we‚Äôve sent rovers, landers, and orbiters to gather the information we'll need to keep future astronauts safe, and with @NASAArtemis, we‚Äôre working on new tech that could one day get humans to Mars. https://t.co/8T8CwvyNqr https://t.co/fDpXjmU6wN

Melba Roy Mouton‚Äîa NASA mathematician and key figure in the Apollo era‚Äîis being honored with the naming of a mountain on the Moon‚Äôs South Pole.

Mons Mouton is the future landing site of VIPER, our rover set to explore the lunar surface for Artemis: https://t.co/Fng8iiGOWp #BHM https://t.co/2tY4EQ9V1Z

@1wKxRlgtJ6sK3fE @NASAspinoff The FINDER prototype was made by @NASAJPL and @dhsscitech. After that initial prototype showed promise, SpecOps Group Inc. of Sarasota, Florida, founded by Adrian Garulay and Tom Coulter, was one of two companies that received licenses to build commercial versions of FINDER.

A @NASASpinoff technology called FINDER has been deployed to aid first responders after the devastating earthquakes in Turkey and Syria. This technology helps rescue teams locate people trapped in rubble. https://t.co/jMkLFWR64f https://t.co/vsEYxvzEfQ

@OriginalSin33 @NASAVoyager The ‚Äúpale blue dot‚Äù image was taken just 34 minutes before Voyager 1 powered off its cameras forever. But don‚Äôt worry; we‚Äôre still communicating with the spacecraft through @NASASCaN. 

Learn how we communicate with spacecraft near and far: https://t.co/Z8iNkOMavP

@ElofLA @NASAVoyager The ‚Äúpale blue dot‚Äù photo was taken by Voyager 1. Still, both @NASAVoyager spacecraft have helped expand our understanding of the solar system while providing gorgeous images as they traverse into interstellar space.

Discover more at: https://t.co/Ly4Mjord87

Our next mission to the @Space_Station is only a couple of weeks away!

#Crew6 is scheduled to lift off from @NASAKennedy on Sunday, Feb. 26‚Äîand if you can't watch the launch in person, there are plenty of ways to join in online: https://t.co/7kas91n7XV https://t.co/7PsCngwCAA

Our planetary defensive player of the year? The #DARTMission, which intercepted an asteroid the size of a football stadium all by itself. Note: The asteroid was well-studied and posed no danger to Earth. https://t.co/2kH057CQD7
But if astronauts used the @Space_Station as a football field, they‚Äôd be the fastest ball-carriers on record, orbiting Earth at 17,500 mph (25,000 kph). https://t.co/b6rViC5CGf

Did you know‚Ä¶.

If the @Space_Station touched down on a football field, they would be about the same size. And the players would have to stop playing. Because that‚Äôd be weird. #SuperBowl https://t.co/OeJ0jeNX9K

"Inside the Ark are treasures beyond your wildest aspirations. You want to see it opened as well as I." Indiana Jones, meet @EuropaClipper.

Ice grows in a vacuum chamber nicknamed "The Ark," built to mimic conditions on an icy Moon of Jupiter. See inside: https://t.co/IyKIvTOxzw https://t.co/iWTU9eUEa0

Watch a Russian Progress cargo spacecraft arrive at the @Space_Station, with docking set for Feb. 11 at 3:49am ET (0849 UTC). NASA TV coverage starts at 3am (0800 UTC): https://t.co/z1RgZwQkWS https://t.co/AN8DsUB657

News from around NASA this week:

Making space for all with @NMAAHC, celebrating the #DARTMission, and spotting a tiny asteroid with @NASAWebb.

@Fulaniyira Depending on where it is in the sky, the Moon can appear smaller or larger. For example, it can look huge when near the horizon‚Äîbut it‚Äôs just a trick of our eyes: https://t.co/r5rmpLHJAj

@Tryansea Mars lost most of its water to space. The rest is now mostly frozen in polar caps, with some also in minerals that have water chemically bound to them, like clays, sulfates, and chlorides. Check out this story for more: https://t.co/buc0zksuhA

A new panorama from @MarsCuriosity provides some of the clearest evidence yet that ancient waves once lapped Martian lakeshores‚Äîin a region that scientists didn't expect: https://t.co/kS4i8PWBgt https://t.co/kzXtJRqLy6

How do we communicate with spacecraft? For decades, satellites have beamed data back to Earth by way of radio waves. Now we're exploring laser communications, @NASA_Technology that will allow us to receive more data from farther than ever before: https://t.co/V5cy10jd4A https://t.co/icXnvNx6ki

Watch a Progress cargo ship, loaded with nearly three tons of food, supplies, and fuel, launch to the @Space_Station on Feb. 9: https://t.co/LD78y0Iy36

@rudydotca We have that in common. üò∂‚Äçüå´Ô∏è

Do you ever see faces in things? That's a phenomenon called pareidolia, and it's when our brains see familiar shapes in objects or data, like in the cloud clouds or the cosmos. Here are some of our favorite examples of pareidolia in space: https://t.co/kwBzhkEYCo https://t.co/onp5BdTuUf

@superturbomira In the unlikely situation where the displays were disabled the X-59 can still be landed using only its canopy, side windows, and data provided by its avionics. We‚Äôve put the displays through an intense array of testing to ensure their reliability: https://t.co/0SkBu6Ugfv
@Ian_Green_ More about how we‚Äôre ensuring the X-59 is up to the standards of our first core value of safety: https://t.co/0SkBu6Ugfv

@Ian_Green_ We‚Äôve put the displays through a gamut of temperature, altitude, vibration, explosive decompression, and gaseous nitrogen environment testing to alleviate breakdowns. Although unlikely, the X-59 can be landed using only its canopy, side windows, and data provided by avionics.

@dockcopper Though astronomers continue to study the finer points of the Milky Way's structure, we can combine what we know about other galaxies in the universe with what we're able to see from Earth to get a general sense of what it looks like. More info: https://t.co/tfSGoL71PX

@SharonSchwager In this case, the elongated and skinny nose of the X-59 prevents a traditional cockpit window from being viable. More about how the X-59 is specially designed to achieve quiet supersonic flight: https://t.co/yYOHuOxYrh

The unique design of @NASAAero's X-59 aircraft means pilots will use a 4K augmented reality display rather than a cockpit window. Some rescue helicopters are already implementing this @NASASpinoff tech to help navigate crowded airspaces: https://t.co/K1dxcOREAS https://t.co/JdRDVtZxF6
@delta_gradient Our X-57 Maxwell hasn‚Äôt taken to the skies yet, but you can follow along as it gets one step closer to that milestone: https://t.co/SGqq8aItBK

@bulbul_319 The X-57 Maxwell weighs about 3,000 pounds (1,360 kgs). We‚Äôre still testing the aircraft and will have a better estimate of range closer to its first flight later this year. Quick X-57 facts: https://t.co/C4uFXBgkwX
@JoeMcAdory We need everybody! We're also looking for interns in communications, business, law, and many other fields‚Äîtake a look at some of our current opportunities: https://t.co/41GhBeuHyT

Heart disease studies and a closer look at space-resistant microbes are among the @ISS_Research on @SpaceX's next cargo resupply mission, scheduled to launch as soon as Friday, March 10.

Applications for media accreditation are due by Wednesday, Feb. 22: https://t.co/HmFIksbZd1 https://t.co/UmpjqzbWxj

@lorraineelkin12 The Moon's core is mostly made up of iron and nickel, with lighter materials closer to the surface. Here's some more info on what's on, in, and around our Moon: https://t.co/87O9urGvL9

@Musketeerguy Yes, though they use much less water than we do back on Earth (to keep it from floating around). This episode of "Houston, We Have A Podcast" takes an in-depth look at how we stay clean on the @Space_Station: https://t.co/BmO3JYPi8w

‚ÄúMy big takeaway is: it's okay to take chances. Sometimes we step in our own way and we need to accept help.‚Äù

With funds from a grant through @NASAArmstrong, scientists studied how arctic ground squirrels retain muscle and bone mass while hibernating, which could apply to future astronauts on long-duration space missions: https://t.co/eDAsA1Imgx https://t.co/9A0zWeINTj

@Alberte_MIFID2 Those are mission patches that stand for the spacecraft built and tested in that room, including both Voyagers, Cassini, and all of our Mars rovers. Select "spacecraft assembly, clean room 1 (center)" on the @NASAJPL virtual tour for a closer look at each: https://t.co/oLUzr963gq

@noshoesonmyFeet @NASAJPL @isro The masks are a standard part of the personal protective gear worn by anyone entering the clean room where a spacecraft is under construction. The gear helps protect the spacecraft and its delicate electronics from particles, including hair and dust.
LIVE: Go inside @NASAJPL for a look at NISAR, an Earth-observing satellite built in partnership with @ISRO. The mission is set to launch from India in 2024. https://t.co/6Hi8AyIQ1D

See NISAR in @NASAJPL's clean room today at 5pm ET (2200 UTC). Set to launch from India in 2024, it will measure the movement of Earth‚Äôs surfaces to provide info on trends that affect global challenges like food security. https://t.co/6Hi8AyIQ1D

We‚Äôre partnering with @ISRO to launch #NISAR, a new satellite that will give us a close-up look at changes in Earth‚Äôs crust using advanced radar imaging. What we learn could help people better manage natural disasters. https://t.co/DY69Nv4vL9 https://t.co/B7eerkATpN

Help us see space from a new perspective!

Try your hand at applying different filters to images captured from our space and ground-based telescopes for the Astrophoto Challenge. The best submissions will be highlighted on the Astrophoto Challenge website: https://t.co/k2AB2I9H4d https://t.co/Ma5rQnMwqo

Is polar ice melting?

Unfortunately, yes. And it‚Äôs the number one contributor to sea level rise. @NASAClimate scientist Dr. Brooke Medley tells us how NASA studies the relationship between ice sheets and sea level to better understand our changing planet. https://t.co/enP5S1HtXz https://t.co/DGNc7gI7w5

@AshleyRaeHart @AstroDuke @Astro_Wakata @Space_Station Spacewalks are limited by the amount of water and oxygen spacesuits can hold, and usually last around 6-7 hours but can go for up to two more hours. 

Temperatures vary from -250 degrees F (-157 C) to 250 degrees F (121 C) as the @Space_Station travels from night to day.

@MichaelHahn56 Once fully installed, the new arrays will provide 20-30% more power generation than before. 

Learn more about the solar arrays here to brighten your day: https://t.co/0YmhWKdq1Q

@JohnTerhorstPhD A few prototype tools were developed then, but not this one. The PGT was invented by former astronaut Paul Richards for Hubble servicing missions. It's programmable so astronauts can preset rotations, speed, direction, and other features.

Ok, here‚Äôs the drill. It‚Äôs called a Pistol Grip Tool, or PGT, and it‚Äôs designed for the extreme environment of space. It works with bulky, pressurized spacesuit gloves like the ones @Astro_Wakata is wearing on the spacewalk happening now. https://t.co/cljvSsWNSN

@AxorityOfficial Great question! We recently announced a project to design and test a new generation of sustainable single-aisle passenger aircraft (which make up most aviation emissions). Learn more about how @NASAAero is committed to sustainable aviation: https://t.co/hlx61msSLI

@Sbowfield1 Time aboard the @Space_Station is the same as on Earth, but we use UTC, or Universal Coordinated Time. Many people know it as GMT. Fun fact: The space station orbits Earth about 16 times in 24 hours, so astronauts experience 16 sunrises and 16 sunsets in one day.

We‚Äôre testing software developed by @NASAAero to help cut your tarmac wait times and make U.S. aviation carbon neutral by 2050.

@mattyjjjames @SenBillNelson The right mitigation strategy for deflecting an asteroid would depend on its size, mass, velocity, and when it was detected. This asteroid is so small, that even if it was on course to hit Earth, which it is not, it would largely burn up harmlessly in the atmosphere.

@BugManInKntucky @SenBillNelson This small asteroid, estimated to be 11.5 to 28 feet (3.5 to 8.5m) across, has no risk of impacting Earth. Even if it did, it'd turn into a fireball and largely disintegrate harmlessly in the atmosphere, with some of the bigger debris potentially falling as small meteorites.

@DrSSWelsh @SenBillNelson That‚Äôs right. Asteroid 2023 BU was discovered by amateur astronomer Gennadiy Borisov on Saturday, Jan. 21, 2023. There is no risk of the asteroid impacting Earth, but even if it did, it would turn into a fireball and largely disintegrate harmlessly in the atmosphere.

@TonyrMurphy1979 @Space_Station @NASA_Johnson #Crew6 will perform dozens of experiments aboard the @Space_Station, including how particular materials burn in microgravity, tissue chip research on heart, brain, and cartilage functions, and collecting microbial samples from the outside of the station. https://t.co/AD3u0JxMWW

@diezelbase Carbon dioxide (CO2) is the primary driver of recent global warming, and it lingers for 1,000s of years. Methane (CH4) is ~80x as effective as CO2 at trapping heat, but dissipates faster. If CH4 emissions are reduced, it will be felt sooner, leading to slower near-term warming.

Methane is far more effective than carbon dioxide at trapping heat in Earth‚Äôs atmosphere. Our new @NASAClimate EMIT mission, designed to measure atmospheric dust, has mapped more than 50 methane ‚Äúsuper-emitters‚Äù around the planet: https://t.co/d4OhBwIeOQ https://t.co/9QLxDMN0nW

@Will1991G The report with the study's findings will be available to the public in mid-2023. One of its goals is to identify what data, from civilian government data, commercial data, and other public data, can potentially be analyzed.
The focus of the study is to inform NASA what possible data could be collected in the future to shed light on UAP. There is no evidence supporting the idea that UAP are extraterrestrial in origin.

@leoalbuq1 Great question! Most lunar samples brought back to Earth by Apollo astronauts have been opened and studied. But some samples collected on the Apollo 15, 16 & 17 missions were kept unopened and pristine, so they could be analyzed with more advanced technologies available today.

@bfcultras Planets (typically) don‚Äôt fall into their star due to conservation of angular momentum. Their orbital motion around a star balances gravitational tugs. But some planets have unstable orbits, and do eventually fall into their stars! Note: The TRAPPIST-1 planets have stable orbits.

@piratefalcon325 @NASAWebb @NASAAstrobio Red dwarfs are truly horrible when they're young, bathing any potential planets in harmful radiation that could influence atmospheric chemistry and possibly strip off these fledgling planets' atmospheres. We're trying to better understand the possible effects of older red dwarfs.

@AshishR81366662 We know 3 of them are in the habitable zone ‚Äî the right orbital distance to be warm enough for liquid water to exist on their surfaces. Astronomers will use @NASAWebb to look for signs of an atmosphere, the next step to finding out if life could survive: https://t.co/THNX8GjW3f

@migzcuad @NASAWebb Light can travel faster than we have the technology to. That said, @NASAWebb will be focusing on studying the atmospheres of these planets to determine which molecules and elements (maybe the building blocks of life!) exist there and what they indicate about the world. (2/2)

@migzcuad @NASAWebb It depends on how far away those planets are! For example, the Trappist system is only 39.4 light years away, so we would be seeing the light that left it 39+ years ago. That doesn't mean we could travel there easily or quickly. (1/2)

@JLCDhome2018 @NASAWebb What is special about this orbit is that it lets the telescope stay in line with the Earth as it moves around the Sun. This allows the satellite's large sunshield to protect the telescope from the light and heat of the Sun and Earth (and Moon): https://t.co/rww0hBX9Ej

@scottparnapy @NASAWebb The sunshield will allow the telescope to cool down to a temperature below 50 Kelvin (-370¬∞F, or -223¬∞C) by passively radiating its heat into space. @NASAWebb‚Äôs MIRI instrument uses a cryocooler to reach its significantly lower operating temperatures of -447¬∞F (7 kelvins).
@JPMajor @NASAWebb Good things come to those who wait! In the meantime, just know we've got a lot of exciting science up ahead: https://t.co/8zPS6MetB4 #UnfoldTheUniverse

@_Crazycrit @NASAWebb As Webb is orbiting L2, it's also moving around the Sun. Since Webb can only point to roughly half the sky at any given moment because it can‚Äôt look in the direction of Earth & the Sun, this affords Webb access to the entire sky over the course of a year: https://t.co/Fv0KXtzKLS

@ianwalkerxx @NASAWebb After @NASAWebb¬†reaches Lagrange point 2 in a few weeks, it will take ~5 months to cool down, align its mirrors & calibrate its instruments before the science begins: https://t.co/2RH2EXQX7a #UnfoldTheUniverse

@bricetune They have a much bigger cryogenic vacuum chamber at @NASA_Johnson that was used on the Apollo program and we tested our mirror and instruments there. The spacecraft (sunshield and bus) were built at Northrop Grumman and they were connected to the mirror/instruments there. (2/2)
@bricetune As big as the vacuum chamber at Goddard is, it isn't big enough for all of Webb! We did test our instrument module there, but after that we had to move the hardware to NASA Johnson. (1/2)

@MetaOracle @NASAWebb Webb can #UnfoldTheUniverse through the infrared spectrum and also has the ability to see a little bit into visible light. Since infrared and visible light are next to each other on the spectrum, @NASAWebb's vision extends just a little bit into the red portion of the visible.

@jamesdmoore614 @NASAHubble @NASAWebb Webb will observe the Ultra Deep Field in our 1st year of science operations. It'll take Webb less than a day to see deeper into the universe than Hubble saw in 2 weeks of staring! It will find tens of thousand of galaxies that are too red & too faint for Hubble to detect.
@PatBarr52364730 The telescope has four science instruments which cover near-infrared through mid-infrared wavelengths, from 0.6 microns up through 28 microns: https://t.co/3dK4AwKDiA
@WangnickS The sunshield has special seams to limit meteorite damage. Testing showed that micrometeoroids have negligible effects on the telescope's beryllium mirrors: https://t.co/Jx1ThKYsPL

@WangnickS Debris isn't an issue a million miles away where we will orbit L2, and space is big so impacts from larger objects (asteroids, meteors) won't be an issue. We do expect tiny micrometeorite impacts, and the telescope was designed and tested for this.

@nachtsmeer The layers, each as thin as a human hair, are made of Kapton, a tough, high-performance plastic. Every layer is coated with aluminum, & the sun-facing side of the two hottest layers also have a doped-silicon (or treated silicon) coating to reflect the sun's heat back into space.

Why is @NASAWebb's sunshield shaped like a kite? In short, it's exactly the shape & size it needs to be.
 
The iconic profile lets the telescope tilt back and forth to observe more of the universe. Plus, it helps radiate heat from the sides. Take a look: https://t.co/YhpDZdWLb8 https://t.co/TjCXoFivq9

@JacksonBTT Splitting the sunshield into 5 layers allows heat to radiate out from between them, causing each successive layer to be cooler than the one below. The vacuum of space between each layer also acts as a great insulator. Learn more about the sunshield design: https://t.co/j1nRsAwHOL
